<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-914-712  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 914 712.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 27 1989 v6 n47 p35(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Publishing program to offer high-quality, scalable fonts. (UnisonWorld's Avagio Publishing System) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Picarille, Lisa.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Unison World's $299.95 Avagio Publishing System offers scalableoutline fonts on DOS systems.andP;  The package producesPostScript-quality print on printers which are not equipped withPostScript.andP;  Type as large as 500 points high has smooth edges onlaser or dot-matrix printers.andP;  Fonts of any size can be generated,and when shown on screen will match printed output exactly.andO;Typefaces similar to Bodoni, Times Roman, Helvetica and NewCentury Schoolbook are included, and a conversion utility allowsLaserJet soft fonts from any vendor to be downloaded.andP;  Text andgraphics can be overlapped.andP;  TIFF and PCX files can be read fromscanners, and clip art and paint program files can be imported.andP;  Amouse, 640Kbytes of RAM and a 20Mbyte hard disk are required.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Unison World Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Avagio Publishing System (Desktop publishing software) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Desktop publishingFontsWord Processing SoftwareCompatibility.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Lisa PicarilleandM;As users await the forthcoming  implementation of scalable outline-fonttechnology on higher-end  platforms such as OS/2 Presentation Manager, UnisonWorld is  promising those capabilities for  the DOS environment now.andM;Unison World's Avagio Publishing System, announced at Comdex/Fall earlierthis month, allows users to create type as  much as 500 points high without jagged edges on any dot-matrix  or laser printer, effectively bringingPostScript-quality output to  non-PostScript printers, claimed  officials atthe Alameda, Calif.,  company.andM;Outline-font technology allows  users to generate fonts of any size  ondemand, the officials explained.andP;  Prior to this technology,  users werelimited to a specific  number of point sizes -- usually  smaller than 36points -- that could be generated on laser or  dot-matrix printers.andM;The fonts Avagio displays on- screen are matched exactly to  print outputbecause they are generated from a single imaging  model, the officials said.andM;The $299.95 program includes  four Unison World typefaces that are similar toTimes Roman, Helvetica, New Century Schoolbook and Bodoni.andM;The software also sports a conversion utility for downloading LaserJet-format soft fonts from any vendor.andP;  This lets users convertEncapsulated PostScript and PostScript files to Unison World's outlineformat, the officials explained.andM;A &quot;mingle&quot; feature allows users to overlap text and graphics.andP;  Users canspecify, for example, that the black part of an object in  the foreground beclear so that  the background shows through.andM;Avagio also can read most popular word processors, including  WordPerfect,Microsoft Word and WordStar.andP;  The program directly reads in the file formats and maintains the attributes associated with the files, such as bold andunderline.andP;  The program can read TIFF and PCX files from  scanners, paintprograms and clip art, officials said.andM;Avagio, slated for delivery in  January, requires an IBM PC or  compatiblewith a 20M-byte hard drive, 640K bytes of RAM and a  mouse.andP;  A standardgraphics card  is recommended.andM;Unison World can be reached  at (415) 748-6670.andO;</TEXT></DOC>